% ===== Page 3 =====
\subsection{Mini-summary of sparsity, small worldness, and strong clustering}

\begin{itemize}
\item Nothing formal can be stated about sparsity, small worldness, or strong clustering in any given (real) network --- all such statements are purely informal and colloquial since they are based on intuition.

\item Yet such statements make perfect formal sense for (random) graph sequences/network models with $n \to \infty$.

\item The causes and effects of these features in real networks are as follows:

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|c|}
\hline
Feature & Sparsity & Small worldness & Clustering \\
\hline
Cause & Cost & Randomness & Geometry \\
\hline
Effect & Cost & Communication & Robustness \\
\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\item The Watts-Strogatz model was the first model that captured all of these three features along with the causes of the last two!

\end{itemize}

